title: Rcpi: R/Bioconductor Package as an Integrated Informatics Platform for Drug Discovery
text: Rcpi package Cao et al. (2015) offers R/Bioconductor package emphasizing comprehensive integration bioinformatics chemoinformatics molecular informatics platform drug discovery. Rcpi implemented integrated state---art protein sequence descriptors molecular descriptors/fingerprints R. protein sequences, Rcpi package can Calculate six protein descriptor groups composed fourteen types commonly used structural physicochemical descriptors include 9,920 descriptors. Calculate profile-based protein representation derived PSSM (Position-Specific Scoring Matrix). Calculate six types generalized scales-based descriptors derived various dimensionality reduction methods proteochemometric (PCM) modeling. Parallellized pairwise similarity computation derived protein sequence alignment Gene Ontology (GO) semantic similarity measures within list proteins. small molecules, Rcpi package can Calculate 307 molecular descriptors (2D/3D), including constitutional, topological, geometrical, electronic descriptors, etc. Calculate ten types molecular fingerprints, including FP4 keys, E-state fingerprints, MACCS keys, etc., parallelized chemical similarity search. Parallelized pairwise similarity computation derived fingerprints maximum common substructure search within list small molecules. combining various types descriptors drugs proteins different methods, interaction descriptors representing protein-protein compound-protein interactions can conveniently generated Rcpi, including: Two types compound-protein interaction (CPI) descriptors Three types protein-protein interaction (PPI) descriptors Several useful auxiliary utilities also shipped Rcpi: Parallelized molecule protein sequence retrieval several online databases, like PubChem, ChEMBL, KEGG, DrugBank, UniProt, RCSB PDB, etc. Loading molecules stored SMILES/SDF files loading protein sequences FASTA/PDB files Molecular file format conversion computed protein sequence descriptors, molecular descriptors/fingerprints, interaction descriptors pairwise similarities widely used various research fields relevant drug disvery, , bioinformatics, chemoinformatics, proteochemometrics chemogenomics.

title: Rcpi: R/Bioconductor Package as an Integrated Informatics Platform for Drug Discovery
text: Protein subcellular localization prediction involves computational prediction protein resides cell. important component bioinformatics-based prediction protein function genome annotation, can also aid us identify novel drug targets. use subcellular localization dataset human proteins presented study Chou Shen (2008) demonstration. complete dataset includes 3,134 protein sequences (2,750 different proteins), classified 14 human subcellular locations. selected two classes proteins benchmark dataset. Class 1 contains 325 extracell proteins, class 2 includes 307 mitochondrion proteins. First, load Rcpi package, read protein sequences stored two separated FASTA files readFASTA(): loaded sequences stored two lists R, component list character string representing one protein sequence. case, 325 extracell protein sequences 306 mitonchon protein sequences: assure protein sequences twenty standard amino acid types required descriptor computation, use checkProt() function amino acid type sanity checking remove non-standard protein sequences: Two protein sequences removed class. remaining sequences, calculate amphiphilic pseudo amino acid composition (APAAC) descriptor Chou (2005) create class labels random forest classification modeling. Rcpi, functions commonly used descriptors protein sequences proteochemometric (PCM) modeling descriptors named extractProt...() extractPCM...(). Next, split data 75% training set 25% test set. train random forest classification model training set 5-fold cross-validation, using package. training result : model trained training set, predict test set plot ROC curve package, shown Figure 1. Figure 1: ROC curve test set protein subcellular localization data. area ROC curve (AUC) :
code: library("Rcpi")  # Load FASTA files extracell <- readFASTA(system.file(   "vignettedata/extracell.fasta",   package = "Rcpi" )) mitonchon <- readFASTA(system.file(   "vignettedata/mitochondrion.fasta",   package = "Rcpi" )) length(extracell) ># [1] 325 length(mitonchon) ># [1] 306 extracell <- extracell[(sapply(extracell, checkProt))] mitonchon <- mitonchon[(sapply(mitonchon, checkProt))] length(extracell) ># [1] 323 length(mitonchon) ># [1] 304 # Calculate APAAC descriptors x1 <- t(sapply(extracell, extractProtAPAAC)) x2 <- t(sapply(mitonchon, extractProtAPAAC)) x <- rbind(x1, x2)  # Make class labels labels <- as.factor(c(rep(0, length(extracell)), rep(1, length(mitonchon)))) set.seed(1001)  # Split training and test set tr.idx <- c(   sample(1:nrow(x1), round(nrow(x1) * 0.75)),   sample(nrow(x1) + 1:nrow(x2), round(nrow(x2) * 0.75)) ) te.idx <- setdiff(1:nrow(x), tr.idx)  x.tr <- x[tr.idx, ] x.te <- x[te.idx, ] y.tr <- labels[tr.idx] y.te <- labels[te.idx] library("randomForest") rf.fit <- randomForest(x.tr, y.tr, cv.fold = 5) print(rf.fit) ># Call: >#  randomForest(x = x.tr, y = y.tr, cv.fold = 5) >#                Type of random forest: classification >#                      Number of trees: 500 ># No. of variables tried at each split: 8 ># >#         OOB estimate of  error rate: 25.11% ># Confusion matrix: >#     0   1 class.error ># 0 196  46   0.1900826 ># 1  72 156   0.3157895 # Predict on test set rf.pred <- predict(rf.fit, newdata = x.te, type = "prob")[, 1]  # Plot ROC curve library("pROC") plot.roc(y.te, rf.pred, grid = TRUE, print.auc = TRUE) ># Call: ># plot.roc.default(x = y.te, predictor = rf.pred, col = "#0080ff", >#                  grid = TRUE, print.auc = TRUE) ># ># Data: rf.pred in 81 controls (y.te 0) > 76 cases (y.te 1). ># Area under the curve: 0.8697

what: Regression modeling in QSRR study of retention indices
title: Rcpi: R/Bioconductor Package as an Integrated Informatics Platform for Drug Discovery
text: Yan et al. (2012), quantitative structure-retention relationship study performed 656 flavor compounds four stationary phases different polarities, using constitutional, topological geometrical molecular descriptors. gas chromatographic retention indices (RIs) compounds accurately predicted using linear models. choose molecules RIs one stationary phase (OV101) benchmark dataset. Since rather tedious implement complete cross-validation procedures, R package caret used . run R code , users need install package required predictive modeling packages first. package provides unified interface modeling tuning task across different statistical machine learning packages. particularly helpful QSAR modeling, contains tools data splitting, pre-processing, feature selection, model tuning functionalities. Just like last section, load Rcpi package, read molecules stored SMILES file: readMolFromSmi() function used reading molecules SMILES files, molecules stored SDF files, use readMolFromSDF() instead. CSV file RI.csv contains tabular data retention indices, compound name, odor information compounds. extracted RI values calling x.tab$RI. molecules properly loaded, calculate several selected molecular descriptors. corresponding functions molecular descriptor calculation named extractDrug...() Rcpi: descriptors calculated, result x data frame, row represents one molecule, column one descriptor (predictor). Rcpi package integrated molecular descriptors chemical fingerprints calculated rcdk package Steinbeck et al. (2003) ChemmineOB package Horan Girke (2013). Next, partial least squares model fitted pls caret package. cross-validation setting 5-fold repeated cross-validation (repeat 10 times). cross-validation result : see RMSE PLS regression model decreasing number principal components (ncomp) increasing. can plot components RMSE helps us select desired number principal components used model. Figure 2: Number principal components vs.¬†RMSE PLS regression model. Figure 2, consider selecting six seven components acceptable. last, plot experimental RIs predicted RIs see model fits well training set (Figure 3): Figure 3: Experimental RIs vs.¬†predicted RIs.
code: library("Rcpi")  RI.smi <- system.file(   "vignettedata/RI.smi",   package = "Rcpi" ) RI.csv <- system.file(   "vignettedata/RI.csv",   package = "Rcpi" )  x.mol <- readMolFromSmi(RI.smi, type = "mol") x.tab <- read.table(RI.csv, sep = "\t", header = TRUE) y <- x.tab$RI # Calculate selected molecular descriptors x <- suppressWarnings(cbind(   extractDrugALOGP(x.mol),   extractDrugApol(x.mol),   extractDrugECI(x.mol),   extractDrugTPSA(x.mol),   extractDrugWeight(x.mol),   extractDrugWienerNumbers(x.mol),   extractDrugZagrebIndex(x.mol) )) # Run regression on training set library("caret") library("pls")  # Cross-validation settings ctrl <- trainControl(   method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 10,   summaryFunction = defaultSummary )  # Train a PLS model set.seed(1002) pls.fit <- train(   x, y,   method = "pls", tuneLength = 10, trControl = ctrl,   metric = "RMSE", preProc = c("center", "scale") )  # Print cross-validation results print(pls.fit) Partial Least Squares   297 samples  10 predictor  Pre-processing: centered (10), scaled (10)  Resampling: Cross-Validated (5 fold, repeated 10 times)  Summary of sample sizes: 237, 239, 238, 237, 237, 238, ...  Resampling results across tuning parameters:    ncomp  RMSE       Rsquared   MAE        1      104.19653  0.8822135  81.30798   2       88.79911  0.9153172  69.67190   3       87.65849  0.9169335  68.90654   4       87.03159  0.9180740  68.45516   5       84.66035  0.9227619  66.65136   6       80.29620  0.9309492  62.57300   7       79.06348  0.9333719  61.51886   8       78.17443  0.9346922  59.81325   9       77.68815  0.9353269  59.48581  RMSE was used to select the optimal model using the smallest value. The final value used for the model was ncomp = 9. # Number of components vs. RMSE print(plot(pls.fit, asp = 0.5)) # Plot experimental RIs vs predicted RIs plot(y, predict(pls.fit, x),   xlim = range(y), ylim = range(y),   xlab = "Experimental RIs", ylab = "Predicted RIs" ) abline(a = 0, b = 1)

what: In silico toxicity classification for drug discovery
title: Rcpi: R/Bioconductor Package as an Integrated Informatics Platform for Drug Discovery
text: perspective quantitative pharmacology, successful discovery novel drugs depends pharmacokinetics properties, like absorption, distribution, metabolism, excretion. addition, potential toxicity chemical compounds taken account. QSAR QSPR methods usually employed predict ADME/T qualities potential drug candidates. D-S Cao et al. (2012), quantitative structure-toxicity relationship (QSTR) models established classifying five toxicity datasets. use maximum recommended daily dose dataset (FDAMDD) FDA Center Drug Evaluation Research benchmark dataset. First, load drug molecules stored SMILES file R: object x.mol used computing MACCS E-state fingerprints; object x.smi used computing FP4 fingerprints. 0-1 class labels stored file FDAMDD.csv indicates whether drug molecule high toxicity . calculate three different types molecular fingerprints (E-state, MACCS, FP4) drug molecules: nature fingerprint-based structure representation, calculated 0-1 matrix x1, x2, x3 sparse. Since several columns nearly exactly value molecules, remove nearZeroVar() caret modeling, split training set test set: training sets, train three classification models separately using SVM (RBF kernel), using kernlab package caret package. cross-validation setting 5-fold repeated CV (repeat 10 times). training result using E-state fingerprints: can see , removing near zero variance predictors, 23 predictors left original 79 E-state fingerprints. training result using MACCS keys: 126 predictors left original 166 MACCS keys removing near-zero variance predictors. model performance AUC values slightly better using E-state fingerprints. training result using FP4 fingerprints: 58 predictors left original 512 FP4 fingerprints screening. model performance AUC values almost comparing using MACCS keys, better using E-state fingerprints. predict test sets established models, plot ROC curves one figure, shown Figure 4. Figure 4: Smoothed ROC curves different fingerprint types.
code: library("Rcpi")  fdamdd.smi <- system.file("vignettedata/FDAMDD.smi", package = "Rcpi") fdamdd.csv <- system.file("vignettedata/FDAMDD.csv", package = "Rcpi")  x.mol <- readMolFromSmi(fdamdd.smi, type = "mol") x.smi <- readMolFromSmi(fdamdd.smi, type = "text") y <- as.factor(paste0("class", scan(fdamdd.csv))) # Calculate molecular fingerprints x1 <- extractDrugEstateComplete(x.mol) x2 <- extractDrugMACCSComplete(x.mol) x3 <- extractDrugOBFP4(x.smi, type = "smile") library("caret")  # Remove near-zero variance variables x1 <- x1[, -nearZeroVar(x1)] x2 <- x2[, -nearZeroVar(x2)] x3 <- x3[, -nearZeroVar(x3)]  # Split training and test set set.seed(1003) tr.idx <- sample(1:nrow(x1), round(nrow(x1) * 0.75)) te.idx <- setdiff(1:nrow(x1), tr.idx) x1.tr <- x1[tr.idx, ] x1.te <- x1[te.idx, ] x2.tr <- x2[tr.idx, ] x2.te <- x2[te.idx, ] x3.tr <- x3[tr.idx, ] x3.te <- x3[te.idx, ] y.tr <- y[tr.idx] y.te <- y[te.idx] # SVM classification on training sets library("kernlab")  # Cross-validation settings ctrl <- trainControl(   method = "cv", number = 5, repeats = 10,   classProbs = TRUE,   summaryFunction = twoClassSummary )  # SVM with RBF kernel svm.fit1 <- train(   x1.tr, y.tr,   method = "svmRadial", trControl = ctrl,   metric = "ROC", preProc = c("center", "scale") ) svm.fit2 <- train(   x2.tr, y.tr,   method = "svmRadial", trControl = ctrl,   metric = "ROC", preProc = c("center", "scale") ) svm.fit3 <- train(   x3.tr, y.tr,   method = "svmRadial", trControl = ctrl,   metric = "ROC", preProc = c("center", "scale") )  # Print cross-validation results print(svm.fit1) print(svm.fit2) print(svm.fit3) ># Support Vector Machines with Radial Basis Function Kernel ># ># 597 samples >#  23 predictors >#   2 classes: "class0", "class1" ># ># Pre-processing: centered, scaled ># Resampling: Cross-Validated (5 fold) ># ># Summary of sample sizes: 478, 479, 477, 477, 477 ># ># Resampling results across tuning parameters: ># >#   C     ROC    Sens   Spec   ROC SD  Sens SD  Spec SD >#   0.25  0.797  0.7    0.765  0.0211  0.0442   0.00666 >#   0.5   0.808  0.696  0.79   0.0173  0.059    0.0236 >#   1     0.812  0.703  0.781  0.0191  0.0664   0.0228 ># ># Tuning parameter "sigma" was held constant at a value of 0.02921559 ># ROC was used to select the optimal model using  the largest value. ># The final values used for the model were sigma = 0.0292 and C = 1. ># Support Vector Machines with Radial Basis Function Kernel ># ># 597 samples ># 126 predictors >#   2 classes: "class0", "class1" ># ># Pre-processing: centered, scaled ># Resampling: Cross-Validated (5 fold) ># ># Summary of sample sizes: 477, 477, 477, 478, 479 ># ># Resampling results across tuning parameters: ># ># 0.0307  0.0229   0.0561 ># ># Tuning parameter "sigma" was held constant at a value of 0.004404305 ># ROC was used to select the optimal model using  the largest value. ># The final values used for the model were sigma = 0.0044 and C = 1. ># Support Vector Machines with Radial Basis Function Kernel ># ># 597 samples >#  58 predictors >#   2 classes: "class0", "class1" ># ># Pre-processing: centered, scaled ># Resampling: Cross-Validated (5 fold) ># ># Summary of sample sizes: 478, 478, 477, 478, 477 ># ># Resampling results across tuning parameters: ># >#   C     ROC    Sens   Spec   ROC SD  Sens SD  Spec SD >#   0.25  0.845  0.769  0.746  0.0498  0.0458   0.0877 >#   0.5   0.856  0.744  0.777  0.0449  0.0148   0.0728 >#   1     0.863  0.751  0.777  0.0428  0.036    0.0651 ># ># Tuning parameter "sigma" was held constant at a value of 0.01077024 ># ROC was used to select the optimal model using  the largest value. ># The final values used for the model were sigma = 0.0108 and C = 1. # Predict on test set svm.pred1 <- predict(svm.fit1, newdata = x1.te, type = "prob")[, 1] svm.pred2 <- predict(svm.fit2, newdata = x2.te, type = "prob")[, 1] svm.pred3 <- predict(svm.fit3, newdata = x3.te, type = "prob")[, 1]  # Generate colors library("RColorBrewer") pal <- brewer.pal(3, "Set1")  # ROC curves of different fingerprints library("pROC") plot(smooth(roc(y.te, svm.pred1)), what: Clustering of molecules based on structural similarities
title: Rcpi: R/Bioconductor Package as an Integrated Informatics Platform for Drug Discovery
text: Apart supervised methods (classification regression), unsupervised approaches, like clustering, also widely applied quantitative research drugs. reality, usually many chemical compounds available identifying drug-like molecules. Thus attractive using clustering methods aid selection representative subset available compounds. clustering approach groups compounds together structural similarity, applying principle similar compounds similar properties means need test representative compounds individual cluster, rather time-consuming complete set experiments, sufficient understand structure-activity relationships whole compound set. Rcpi package provides easy--use functions computing similarity small molecules derived molecular fingerprints maximum common substructure search. example, SDF file tyrphostin.sdf database composed searching tyrphostin PubChem filtered Lipinski‚Äùs rule five. load SDF file using readMolFromSDF(): compute E-state fingerprints molecules using extractDrugEstate(), calculate pairwise similarity matrix calcDrugFPSim(): computed similarity matrix simmat, try cluster molecules using hierarchical clustering, visualize clustering result: hierarchical clustering result molecules shown Figure 5. Figure 5: Tree visualization molecular clustering result.
code: library("Rcpi") mols <- readMolFromSDF(system.file(   "compseq/tyrphostin.sdf",   package = "Rcpi" )) simmat <- diag(length(mols))  for (i in 1:length(mols)) {   for (j in i:length(mols)) {     fp1 <- extractDrugEstate(mols[[i]])     fp2 <- extractDrugEstate(mols[[j]])     tmp <- calcDrugFPSim(fp1, fp2, fptype = "compact", metric = "tanimoto")     simmat[i, j] <- tmp     simmat[j, i] <- tmp   } } mol.hc <- hclust(as.dist(1 - simmat), method = "ward.D")  library("ape") # Tree visualization of clusters clus5 <- cutree(mol.hc, 5) # Cut dendrogram into 5 clusters  # Generate colors library("RColorBrewer") pal5 <- brewer.pal(5, "Set1") plot(as.phylo(mol.hc),   type = "fan",   tip.color = pal5[clus5],   label.offset = 0.1, cex = 0.7 )

code: library("Rcpi")  mol <- system.file("compseq/DB00530.sdf", package = "Rcpi") moldb <- system.file("compseq/tyrphostin.sdf", package = "Rcpi") rank1 <- searchDrug(   mol, moldb,   cores = 4, method = "fp",   fptype = "maccs", fpsim = "tanimoto" ) rank2 <- searchDrug(   mol, moldb,   cores = 4, method = "fp",   fptype = "fp2", fpsim = "cosine" ) rank3 <- searchDrug(   mol, moldb,   cores = 4, method = "mcs",   mcssim = "tanimoto" ) head(rank1) >#        92       100        83       101         1        36 ># 0.6491228 0.6491228 0.5882353 0.5660377 0.5000000 0.4861111 head(rank2) >#       100        92        83       101        94        16 ># 0.8310005 0.8208663 0.5405856 0.5033150 0.4390790 0.4274081 head(rank3) >#        92       100        23        39        94        64 ># 0.7000000 0.7000000 0.4000000 0.4000000 0.4000000 0.3783784 # Convert SDF format to SMILES format convMolFormat(   infile = mol, outfile = "DB00530.smi", from = "sdf", to = "smiles" ) convMolFormat(   infile = moldb, outfile = "tyrphostin.smi", from = "sdf", to = "smiles" )  smi1 <- readLines("DB00530.smi") smi2 <- readLines("tyrphostin.smi")[92] # Select the #92 molecule calcDrugMCSSim(smi1, smi2, type = "smile", plot = TRUE) ># [[1]] ># An instance of "MCS" >#  Number of MCSs: 1 >#  530: 29 atoms >#  4705: 22 atoms >#  MCS: 18 atoms >#  Tanimoto Coefficient: 0.54545 >#  Overlap Coefficient: 0.81818 ># ># [[2]] ># Tanimoto_Coefficient >#            0.5454545 ># ># [[3]] ># Overlap_Coefficient >#           0.8181818

what: Predicting drug-target interaction by integrating chemical and genomic spaces
title: Rcpi: R/Bioconductor Package as an Integrated Informatics Platform for Drug Discovery
text: prediction novel interactions drugs target proteins key area genomic drug discovery. example, use G Protein-Coupled Receptor (GPCR) dataset provided Yamanishi et al. (2008) benchmark dataset. drug-target interaction network can naturally modeled bipartite graph, nodes target proteins drug molecules edges (drugs proteins connected edges) represent drug-target interactions. Initially, graph contains edges describing real drug-target interactions determined experiments ways. example, real drug-target interaction pairs (.e., 635 drug-target interactions) used positive samples. negative samples select random, non-interacting pairs drugs proteins. constructed follows: Separate pairs positive samples single drugs proteins; Re-couple singles pairs way none occurs corresponding positive dataset. Ten generated negative sets used Dong-Sheng Cao et al. (2012), used one demonstration. drug ID target ID stored GPCR.csv. first column KEGG protein ID, second column KEGG drug ID. first 635 rows form positive set, last 635 rows form negative set. Take look data: visualize network first. Figure 7 shows connection pattern GPCR drug-target interaction network form arc diagram. Figure 7: Arc diagram visualization GPCR drug-target interaction network. arc diagram visualize nodes network one-dimensional layout, using circular arcs represent edges. good ordering nodes, easy identify cliques bridges. Next, download target protein sequences (FASTA format) drug molecule (SMILES format) KEGG database, parallel: connection slow accidentally interrupts, just try times success. functions Rcpi named getMolFrom...() getSmiFrom...() supports parallelized retrieval (drug) molecules PubChem, ChEMBL, CAS, KEGG, DrugBank. functions named getSeqFrom...(), getFASTAFrom...(), getPDBFrom...() supports parallelized retrieval proteins UniProt, KEGG RCSB PDB. functions getDrug() getProt() two integrated wrapper functions downloading molecules protein sequences online databases. sequences downloaded, can calculate protein sequence descriptors molecular descriptors targets drugs: Since descriptors deduplicated drug target list, need generate full descriptor matrix training data: Generate drug-target interaction descriptors using getCPI(). pairwise interaction another useful type representation drug-target prediction, protein-protein interaction prediction related research. Rcpi also provides getPPI() generate protein-protein interaction descriptors. getPPI() provides three types interactions getCPI() provides two types. argument type used control .
code: library("Rcpi")  gpcr <- read.table(system.file(   "vignettedata/GPCR.csv",   package = "Rcpi" ), header = FALSE, as.is = TRUE ) head(gpcr) >#          V1     V2 ># 1 hsa:10161 D00528 ># 2 hsa:10800 D00411 ># 3 hsa:10800 D01828 ># 4 hsa:10800 D05129 ># 5 hsa:11255 D00234 ># 6 hsa:11255 D00300 library("igraph") library("reshape") # remotes::install_github("gastonstat/arcdiagram") library("arcdiagram")  g <- graph.data.frame(gpcr[1:(nrow(gpcr) / 2), ], directed = FALSE) edgelist <- get.edgelist(g) vlabels <- V(g)$name vgroups <- c(rep(0, 95), rep(1, 223)) vfill <- c(rep("#8B91D4", 95), rep("#B2C771", 223)) vborders <- c(rep("#6F74A9", 95), rep("#8E9F5A", 223)) degrees <- degree(g)  xx <- data.frame(vgroups, degrees, vlabels, ind = 1:vcount(g)) yy <- arrange(xx, desc(vgroups), desc(degrees)) new.ord <- yy$ind  arcplot(   edgelist,   ordering = new.ord, labels = vlabels,   cex.labels = 0.1, show.nodes = TRUE,   col.nodes = vborders, bg.nodes = vfill,   cex.nodes = log10(degrees) + 0.1,   pch.nodes = 21, line = -0.5, col.arcs = hsv(0, 0, 0.2, 0.25) ) library("Rcpi")  gpcr <- read.table(system.file(   "vignettedata/GPCR.csv",   package = "Rcpi" ), header = FALSE, as.is = TRUE )  protid <- unique(gpcr[, 1]) drugid <- unique(gpcr[, 2])  protseq <- getSeqFromKEGG(protid, parallel = 5) drugseq <- getSmiFromKEGG(drugid, parallel = 50) x0.prot <- cbind(   t(sapply(unlist(protseq), extractProtAPAAC)),   t(sapply(unlist(protseq), extractProtCTriad)) )  x0.drug <- cbind(   extractDrugEstateComplete(readMolFromSmi(textConnection(drugseq))),   extractDrugMACCSComplete(readMolFromSmi(textConnection(drugseq))),   extractDrugOBFP4(drugseq, type = "smile") ) # Generate drug x / protein x / y x.prot <- matrix(NA, nrow = nrow(gpcr), ncol = ncol(x0.prot)) x.drug <- matrix(NA, nrow = nrow(gpcr), ncol = ncol(x0.drug)) for (i in 1:nrow(gpcr)) x.prot[i, ] <- x0.prot[which(gpcr[, 1][i] == protid), ] for (i in 1:nrow(gpcr)) x.drug[i, ] <- x0.drug[which(gpcr[, 2][i] == drugid), ]  y <- as.factor(c(rep("pos", nrow(gpcr) / 2), rep("neg", nrow(gpcr) / 2))) x <- getCPI(x.prot, x.drug, type = "combine")

Train random forest classification model 5-fold repeated CV: Print cross-validation result: Predict training set (demonstration purpose ) plot ROC curve. ROC curve shown Figure 8. Figure 8: ROC curve predicting training set GPCR drug-target interaction dataset using random forest.
code: library("caret") x <- x[, -nearZeroVar(x)]  # Cross-validation settings ctrl <- trainControl(   method = "cv", number = 5, repeats = 10,   classProbs = TRUE,   summaryFunction = twoClassSummary )  # Train a random forest classifier library("randomForest")  set.seed(1006) rf.fit <- train(   x, y,   method = "rf", trControl = ctrl,   metric = "ROC", preProc = c("center", "scale") ) print(rf.fit) ># Random Forest ># ># 1270 samples >#  562 predictors >#    2 classes: "neg", "pos" ># ># Pre-processing: centered, scaled ># Resampling: Cross-Validated (5 fold) ># ># Summary of sample sizes: 1016, 1016, 1016, 1016, 1016 ># ># Resampling results across tuning parameters: ># >#   mtry  ROC    Sens   Spec   ROC SD  Sens SD  Spec SD >#   2     0.83   0.726  0.778  0.0221  0.044    0.0395 >#   33    0.882  0.795  0.82   0.018   0.0522   0.0443 >#   562   0.893  0.822  0.844  0.0161  0.0437   0.0286 ># ># ROC was used to select the optimal model using  the largest value. ># The final value used for the model was mtry = 562. rf.pred <- predict(rf.fit$finalModel, x, type = "prob")[, 1]  library("pROC") plot(smooth(roc(y, rf.pred)), grid = TRUE, print.auc = TRUE)

title: Calculate Drug Molecule Similarity Derived by Molecular Fingerprints ‚Äî calcDrugFPSim
text: function calculate drug molecule fingerprints similarity. Define features object , b features object B, c number common features B: Tanimoto: aka Jaccard - \(c/+b+c\) Euclidean: \(\sqrt(+ b)\) Dice: aka Sorensen, Czekanowski, Hodgkin-Richards - \(c/0.5[(+c) + (b+c)]\) Cosine: aka Ochiai, Carbo - \(c/\sqrt((+ c)(b + c))\) Hamming: aka Manhattan, taxi-cab, city-block distance - \((+ b)\)

title: Calculate Atom Additive logP and Molar Refractivity Values Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugALOGP
text: Calculates ALOGP (Ghose-Crippen LogKow) Ghose-Crippen molar refractivity described Ghose, .K. Crippen, G.M. Note underlying code CDK assumes aromaticity detected evaluating descriptor. code also expects molecule hydrogens explicitly set. SD files, usually problem since hydrogens explicit. case molecules obtained SMILES, hydrogens must made explicit.

title: Calculate Atom Additive logP and Molar Refractivity Values Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugALOGP
text: Ghose, .K. Crippen, G.M. , Atomic physicochemical parameters three-dimensional structure-directed quantitative structure-activity relationships. . Partition coefficients measure hydrophobicity, Journal Computational Chemistry, 1986, 7:565-577. Ghose, .K. Crippen, G.M. , Atomic physicochemical parameters three-dimensional-structure-directed quantitative structure-activity relationships. 2. Modeling dispersive hydrophobic interactions, Journal Chemical Information Computer Science, 1987, 27:21-35.

title: BCUT -- Eigenvalue Based Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugBCUT
text: Eigenvalue based descriptor noted utility chemical diversity. Described Pearlman et al. descriptor based weighted version Burden matrix takes account connectivity well atomic properties molecule. weights variety atom properties placed along diagonal Burden matrix. Currently three weighting schemes employed: Atomic Weight Partial Charge (Gasteiger Marsilli) Polarizability (Kang et al.)

title: BCUT -- Eigenvalue Based Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugBCUT
text: default, descriptor return highest lowest eigenvalues three classes descriptor single ArrayList (order shown ). However also possible supply parameter list indicating many highest lowest eigenvalues (class descriptor) required. descriptor works hydrogen depleted molecule. side effect specifying number highest lowest eigenvalues possible get two copies eigenvalues. , molecule 5 heavy atoms, specifying 5 highest eigenvalues returns , specifying 5 lowest eigenvalues returns , resulting two copies eigenvalues. Note possible specify arbitrarily large number eigenvalues returned. However number (.e., nhigh nlow) larger number heavy atoms, remaining eignevalues NaN. Given description, aim gt eigenvalues molecule, set nlow 0 specify number heavy atoms (large number) nhigh (vice versa).

title: BCUT -- Eigenvalue Based Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugBCUT
text: Pearlman, R.S. Smith, K.M., Metric Validation Receptor-Relevant Subspace Concept, J. Chem. Inf. Comput. Sci., 1999, 39:28-35. Burden, F.R., Molecular identification number substructure searches, J. Chem. Inf. Comput. Sci., 1989, 29:225-227. Burden, F.R., Chemically Intuitive Molecular Index, Quant. Struct. -Act. Relat., 1997, 16:309-314 Kang, Y.K. Jhon, M.S., Additivity Atomic Static Polarizabilities Dispersion Coefficients, Theoretica Chimica Acta, 1982, 61:41-48

code: mol1 = 'CC(=O)NCCC1=CNc2c1cc(OC)cc2'  # one molecule SMILE in a vector mol2 = c('OCCc1c(C)[n+](=cs1)Cc2cnc(C)nc(N)2',          'CCc(c1)ccc2[n+]1ccc3c2Nc4c3cccc4',          '[Cu+2].[O-]S(=O)(=O)[O-]')  # multiple SMILEs in a vector mol3 = readChar(system.file('compseq/DB00860.sdf', package = 'Rcpi'),                 nchars = 1e+6)  # single molecule in a sdf file mol4 = readChar(system.file('sysdata/OptAA3d.sdf', package = 'Rcpi'),                 nchars = 1e+6)  # multiple molecules in a sdf file  if (FALSE) { smidesc0 = extractDrugDescOB(mol1, type = 'smile') smidesc1 = extractDrugDescOB(mol2, type = 'smile') sdfdesc0 = extractDrugDescOB(mol3, type = 'sdf') sdfdesc1 = extractDrugDescOB(mol4, type = 'sdf')}

title: Calculate the Eccentric Connectivity Index Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugECI
text: Eccentric Connectivity Index (ECI) topological descriptor combining distance adjacency information. descriptor described Sharma et al. shown correlate well number physical properties. descriptor also reported good discriminatory ability. eccentric connectivity index hydrogen supressed molecular graph given $$x_i^c = \sum_{= 1}^{n} E() V()$$ E() eccentricity -th atom (path length -th atom atom farthest ) V() vertex degree -th atom.

title: Calculate the Eccentric Connectivity Index Descriptor ‚Äî extractDrugECI

title: Calculate Holistic Descriptors Described by Todeschini et al. ‚Äî extractDrugWHIM
text: Holistic descriptors described Todeschini et al, descriptors based number atom weightings. six different possible weightings: unit weights atomic masses van der Waals volumes Mulliken atomic electronegativites atomic polarizabilities E-state values described Kier Hall Currently weighting schemes 1, 2, 3, 4 5 implemented. weight values taken Todeschini et al. result 19 elements considered. weighting scheme can obtain 11 directional WHIM descriptors (lambda1 .. 3, nu1 .. 2, gamma1 .. 3, eta1 .. 3) 6 non-directional WHIM descriptors (T, , V, K, G, D) Though Todeschini et al. mentions planar molecules 8 directional WHIM descriptors required current code return 11.

code: extractProtPSSM(   seq,   start.pos = 1L,   end.pos = nchar(seq),   psiblast.path = NULL,   makeblastdb.path = NULL,   database.path = NULL,   iter = 5,   silent = TRUE,   evalue = 10L,   word.size = NULL,   gapopen = NULL,   gapextend = NULL,   matrix = "BLOSUM62",   threshold = NULL,   seg = "no",   soft.masking = FALSE,   culling.limit = NULL,   best.hit.overhang = NULL,   best.hit.score.edge = NULL,   xdrop.ungap = NULL,   xdrop.gap = NULL,   xdrop.gap.final = NULL,   window.size = NULL,   gap.trigger = 22L,   num.threads = 1L,   pseudocount = 0L,   inclusion.ethresh = 0.002 )

title: Compute PSSM (Position-Specific Scoring Matrix) for given protein sequence ‚Äî extractProtPSSM
text: seq Character vector, input protein sequence. start.pos Optional integer denoting start position fragment window. Default 1, .e. first amino acid given sequence. end.pos Optional integer denoting end position fragment window. Default nchar(seq), .e. last amino acid given sequence. psiblast.path Character string indicating path psiblast program. NCBI Blast+ previously installed operation system, path automatically detected. makeblastdb.path Character string indicating path makeblastdb program. NCBI Blast+ previously installed system, path automatically detected. database.path Character string indicating path reference database (FASTA file). iter Number iterations perform PSI-Blast. silent Logical. Whether PSI-Blast running output shown (May work Windows versions PSI-Blast versions), default TRUE. evalue Expectation value (E) threshold saving hits. Default 10. word.size Word size wordfinder algorithm. integer >= 2. gapopen Integer. Cost open gap. gapextend Integer. Cost extend gap. matrix Character string. scoring matrix name (default 'BLOSUM62'). threshold Minimum word score word added BLAST lookup table. real value >= 0. seg Character string. Filter query sequence SEG ('yes', 'window locut hicut', '' disable) Default ''. soft.masking Logical. Apply filtering locations soft masks? Default FALSE. culling.limit integer >= 0. query range hit enveloped least many higher-scoring hits, delete hit. Incompatible best.hit.overhang best_hit_score_edge. best.hit.overhang Best Hit algorithm overhang value (real value >= 0 =< 0.5, recommended value: 0.1). Incompatible culling_limit. best.hit.score.edge Best Hit algorithm score edge value (real value >=0 =< 0.5, recommended value: 0.1). Incompatible culling_limit. xdrop.ungap X-dropoff value (bits) ungapped extensions. xdrop.gap X-dropoff value (bits) preliminary gapped extensions. xdrop.gap.final X-dropoff value (bits) final gapped alignment. window.size integer >= 0. Multiple hits window size, specify 1-hit algorithm, use 0. gap.trigger Number bits trigger gapping. Default 22. num.threads Integer. Number threads (CPUs) use BLAST search. Default 1. pseudocount Integer. Pseudo-count value used constructing PSSM. Default 0. inclusion.ethresh E-value inclusion threshold pairwise alignments. Default 0.002.

text: mol query molecule. location sdf file containing one molecule. moldb molecule database. location sdf file containing molecules searched . cores Integer. number CPU cores use parallel search, default 2. Users use detectCores() function parallel package see many cores use. method 'fp' 'mcs'. Search molecular fingerprints maximum common substructure searching. fptype fingerprint type, available method = 'fp'. Rcpi supports 13 types fingerprints, including 'standard', 'extended', 'graph', 'hybrid', 'maccs', 'estate', 'pubchem', 'kr', 'shortestpath', 'fp2', 'fp3', 'fp4', 'obmaccs'. fpsim Similarity measure type fingerprint, available method = 'fp'. Including 'tanimoto', 'euclidean', 'cosine', 'dice' 'hamming'. See calcDrugFPSim details. mcssim Similarity measure type maximum common substructure search, available method = 'mcs'. Including 'tanimoto' 'overlap'. ... possible parameter maximum common substructure search, see calcDrugMCSSim available options.
